import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    box_plot = data.boxplot(column='total', by='region')
    plt.title("What is the distribution of total income across different regions?")
    plt.suptitle("")
    plt.xlabel("Region")
    plt.ylabel("Total Income")
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        box_plot.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    avg_income_per_capita = data.groupby('region')['total'].mean()
    avg_income_per_capita.plot(kind='bar')
    
    plt.title("What is the average income per capita in each region?")
    plt.xlabel("Region")
    plt.ylabel("Average Income Per Capita")
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    # Group data by region and income group
    grouped_data = data.groupby(['region', 'group']).agg({'total': 'sum'}).reset_index()
    
    # Pivot the data to create a stacked bar chart
    pivot_data = grouped_data.pivot_table(index='region', columns='group', values='total', fill_value=0)
    
    # Plot the stacked bar chart
    pivot_data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=plt.gca())
    
    # Rotate x-axis labels if necessary
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.title("What is the distribution of income groups across different regions?")
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    for region in data['region'].unique():
        region_data = data[data['region'] == region]
        plt.scatter(region_data['total'], region_data['pct'], label=region)
    
    plt.xlabel('Total Income')
    plt.ylabel('Population')
    plt.legend(title='Region')
    plt.title('What is the correlation between income and population in each region?')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    # Pivot the data to get the percentage of each income group by state
    pivot_data = data.pivot_table(index='name', columns='group', values='pct', aggfunc='sum')
    
    # Plot the stacked bar chart
    pivot_data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=plt.gca())
    
    # Rotate x-axis labels if necessary
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.title("What is the distribution of income groups within each state?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
